<seg id="1042">If a picture is rendered with only one beam per pixel, different errors can occur. these images often have a moiré pattern or step effects in curves and lines, and sometimes details will not be displayed if they are smaller than a pixel in the representation. this effect is called aliasing.</seg>
<seg id="1043">& Povray; uses a technique called anti-aliasing to reduce the impact of these errors. generally, pictures with this property look better.</seg>
<seg id="1044">If you turn on anti-aliasing, calculate and connect & Povray; more than one beam per pixel. this technique is super-sampling.</seg>
<seg id="1045">& Povray; supports two methods of super-sampling. the default is an adaptive, non-recursive method; adaptive because the super-sampling refers to the neighbouring pixels. the second method is adaptive-recursive; recursive, because each pixel is continuously divided and adapted because the recursion depth depends on the calculated color values.</seg>
<seg id="1046">If you choose the first method POV-Ray tracks a beam per pixel. if the difference between the color values exceeds the given threshold, both pixels are calculated by tracking a certain additional number of pixels with super-sampling. if you set the depth value to 4, a grid of 4x4 additional points will be calculated, with a depth value of 5 then 5x5 (25) additional rays per pixel.</seg>
<seg id="1047">The difference between two pixels is calculated as follows: r 1, g 1 and b 1 are the values for red, green and blue of the first pixel, r 2, g 2 and b 2 are the values for red, green and blue of the second pixel. the difference is then:</seg>
<seg id="1048">Diff = abs (r 1 -r 2) + abs (g 1 -g 2) + abs (b 1 -b 2)</seg>
<seg id="1049">The recursive method starts with 4 beams per pixel. if the difference between the color values exceeds the given threshold, the pixel is split into 4 sub-pixels, which are pursued individually and are checked for further subdivision. the maximum depth of the recursion can be set with the depth value.</seg>
